before <strong>Karen Bass</strong> and <strong>Rick Caruso</strong> were in=
 politics, and before climate change became the left=E2=80=99s doomsday exp=
lanation for everything=E2=80=94the chaparral-flecked mountains of Southern=
 California burned. From Malibu to Eaton Canyon, and down in Laguna Beach, =
the hot Santa Ana winds fueled wildfires that scorched tens of thousands of=
 acres and razed hundreds of homes in 1993. Celebrities fled their burning
mansions down narrow canyon roads, running alongside average middle-class h=
omeowners whose places had become a precious source of generational wealth =
thanks to the region=E2=80=99s soaring property values.=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">Looters prowled the abandoned neighborhoods. Republicans blamed va=
grants for arson=E2=80=94and, indeed, arson was found to be the cause of so=
me of the fires. City and county agencies bickered with each other in
the aftermath. In Laguna, angry victims and greedy developers presaged toda=
y=E2=80=99s D.E.I. finger-pointing, blaming a gay city council member for d=
evoting =E2=80=9Ctoo much attention to AIDS victims and not enough on fire =
protection.=E2=80=9D Eager to rebuild and reclaim their stunning hillside v=
iews of the Pacific, wealthy liberals begged Democratic leaders to neuter t=
he California Coastal Commission and its environmental protections.=C2=A0</=
p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"=
>I=E2=80=99m
cribbing these stories from <em>Ecology of Fear</em>, <strong>Mike Davis</s=
trong>=E2=80=99s seminal book about Los Angeles and =E2=80=9Cthe imaginatio=
n of disaster,=E2=80=9D which was available on Amazon last week, but has si=
nce sold out in the wake of the fires and devil winds that continue to wrea=
k havoc on the Southland. One chapter in particular, =E2=80=9CThe Case for =
Letting Malibu Burn,=E2=80=9D has been making the rounds out here, partly f=
or its prescience about the current devastation in Los Angeles and the huma=
n blame games
that ensue. But his essay is also a reminder that the flames are not solely=
 the result of climate change, which is what the social media manager at th=
e D.N.C. would like you to believe. The Los Angeles Basin is its own peculi=
ar ecosystem, veering between wet winters and dry ones, with Santa Ana wind=
s and tinderbox scrub that have sparked fires every few years since, well, =
forever.</p></div>
