</td></tr></tbody></table>
<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">People in Los Angeles are, for the most part, f=
ocused on helping
their friends and loved ones who lost everything. They are also focused on =
helping strangers. On Sunday night in Arcadia, at a donation center in Sant=
a Anita Park for victims of the Eaton Fire, volunteers had to stop acceptin=
g donations because there were too many people showing up to help. All over=
 the city, Angelenos are sheltering pets. Firefighters are doing the lord=
=E2=80=99s work. A trio of my friends in Venice raised several thousand dol=
lars over Instagram and Venmo to buy supplies for the
neighborhood firefighters, just one platoon in an army of heroes who have b=
een laying hose up and down the steep, brush-choked ravines of the Palisade=
s to fight the blaze.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">My friends showed up at one=
 Venice firehouse with pallets of water, but it turned out the firefighters=
 wanted Zyns, Celsius, and breakfast food even more. So they went back out =
and bought those, too. Spreadsheets are being
organized for victims and passed around in group chats, listing all those t=
hings you need but don=E2=80=99t think about taking with you when a fire is=
 racing down a hill toward your home: underwear, toys, pet food, blankets, =
diapers, a yoga mat, something as simple as a nail clipper.=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bo=
ttom:0px;">This sort of fellowship and generosity, unusual for such a spraw=
ling and diverse city which remains remarkably stratified by
class and race, is what most people in Los Angeles are focused on. But ther=
e is the obnoxious and inescapable background noise of social media, too, w=
ith partisans and clout-chasers rushing to X and TikTok and elsewhere to po=
st about why the fires are the logical outcome in the failed dystopia of li=
beral California. Even the incoming president, himself, couldn=E2=80=99t re=
sist posting about <strong>Gavin </strong>=E2=80=9CNewscum=E2=80=9D and Cal=
ifornia=E2=80=99s supposedly incompetent leadership, as the death toll was =
rising
in the nation=E2=80=99s largest state.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Musk tried=
 to prove this out in his own icky way, meeting with local firefighters on =
Sunday and streaming it live on X, trying to bait the first responders into=
 saying they didn=E2=80=99t have enough water to combat the Palisades fire =
thanks to inept Democrats. But the firefighters wouldn=E2=80=99t bite. They=
 told Musk they did, in fact, have enough water. It=E2=80=99s just that the=
 blaze was
so massive the water system couldn=E2=80=99t sustain the flow. It was an in=
convenient truth for Musk, who, like other MAGA screen addicts last week, c=
ouldn=E2=80=99t resist posting about politics, rather than displaying a shr=
ed of humanity, even as the first plume of smoke rose up over the mountains=
=2E Babies=E2=80=99 cribs were incinerated=
, while grandparents watched a life=
time of memories turned into ash. I can report confidently, from multiple s=
ources here on the ground, that most Angelenos would like the social media
brigade to shut the fuck up.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At the same time, Bass, =
elected mayor just over two years ago after years in Congress, has emerged =
as the singular public figure that even liberal Los Angeles is done with. I=
t=E2=80=99s not because she may or may not have cut the fire department bud=
get, or left a reservoir empty, or didn=E2=80=99t do enough to clean up bru=
sh and vegetation around the city, although those questions are fair.
Voters in Los Angeles, generally, understand that their mayor has relativel=
y little power compared to executives in other cities=E2=80=94that the City=
 Council has the real muscle, and that Los Angeles County has its own servi=
ces and responsibilities that overlap with the city=E2=80=99s or operate in=
dependently from it. Local government in L.A. is as balkanized as its neigh=
borhoods. People understand there are no easy solutions, and it will take t=
ime to learn all the facts about why the blazes were so
ruinous.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">The bigger issue=E2=80=94the main issue=
=E2=80=94is that Bass lost the public trust in spectacular fashion. The Nat=
ional Weather Service warned of dangerous fire conditions on Friday, Januar=
y 3. Bass knew about it, because we all did. If you live in L.A., you got t=
he weather alert, on the news or on your phone. The mayor=E2=80=99s office =
certainly did. Despite that, Bass boarded a plane the following day for Gha=
na
as part of a delegation attending the inauguration of the country=E2=80=99s=
 president. And as <em>The New York Times </em>reported over the weekend, B=
ass had promised during her mayoral campaign <em>never</em> to leave the co=
untry. It got worse on the return trip=E2=80=94a long way home=E2=80=94when=
 a Sky News reporter happened upon Bass and an aide at the airport. The rep=
orter asked Bass, repeatedly, to deliver a message to the city. Bass ignore=
d him, on camera, for 90 painful seconds, in stone-faced silence. The clip
is devastating, a campaign ad ready-made, the moment for which she will alw=
ays be remembered. =E2=80=9CIf it is true that she left the country on a Sa=
turday after the warning came out, that is a dereliction of duty,=E2=80=9D =
Endeavor C.E.O. <strong>Ari Emanuel</strong>, who donated to Bass=E2=80=99s=
 2022 campaign, told me.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Backers of billionaire r=
eal estate developer Rick Caruso=E2=80=94Bass=E2=80=99s once and possibly f=
uture rival for
mayor=E2=80=94also smell blood in water ahead of next year=E2=80=99s electi=
on, if a recall doesn=E2=80=99t come first, which is a real possibility, ev=
en though it would require a mountain of verified signatures from Los Angel=
es voters. But as one Democratic strategist told me, =E2=80=9CYou never kno=
w. The anger is there.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">UTA superag=
ent <strong>Jay Sures</strong>, one of Caruso=E2=80=99s biggest donors and =
loudest advocates in the
2022 mayor=E2=80=99s race, told me that Bass=E2=80=99s performance has been=
 <em>disqualifying</em> and <em>unforgivable</em>. =E2=80=9CTo me, it=E2=80=
=99s utter incompetence at the highest level with the mayor=E2=80=99s offic=
e,=E2=80=9D Sures told me. =E2=80=9CThe fact that she was not here on stand=
by and ready to go? It=E2=80=99s unforgivable. At the end of the day, we el=
ect leaders who are supposed to represent us and protect us and be there fo=
r us in times of need. That=E2=80=99s what we expect. Information should be=
 forthright and available at a moment=E2=80=99s notice.
Why are we getting all of our alerts from private apps? At the end of the d=
ay, we don=E2=80=99t need positive words right now. We need action. We need=
 people to get in to see their homes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:=
0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Ne=
wsom, meanwhile, has been all over the news, and more or less acting like t=
he <em>de facto</em> leader of Los Angeles in the absence of clear and cons=
istent communication from the mayor. Even if he comes off as famously
stiff, Newsom has been flooding the zone as people look for direction=E2=80=
=94meeting with victims, issuing executive orders, sending supplies, and sa=
ying <em>yes</em> to every interview. Bass? She=E2=80=99s been showing up a=
t her news conferences, throwing to other officials, and posting every so o=
ften on social media, with banal talking points that no one wants to hear. =
=E2=80=9CThese fires across our region have changed lives forever,=E2=80=9D=
 went one X post on Saturday. =E2=80=9CThe days ahead will be challenging b=
ut we WILL get
through this crisis, together.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margi=
n-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">How, though? <strong>Jonath=
an Vigliotti</strong> of CBS News asked Bass at a press conference over the=
 weekend how the government can restore trust with locals who =E2=80=9Care =
losing faith.=E2=80=9D Somewhere in her meandering answer, Bass said that =
=E2=80=9Csuccess has been reported=E2=80=9D and that =E2=80=9Cwe are not go=
ing to let politics divide us.=E2=80=9D Behind her, city officials shuffled=
 around uncomfortably.</p></div>
